AS INTRODUCED
5
6
An Act relating to the Pretrial Release Act; amending
6
22 O.S. 2021, Section 1105.2, which relates to
7
conditions of release; requiring judicial districts
7
to utilize certain risk assessments; requiring
8
assessment to be provided to certain counsel;
8
requiring assessment to include certain information;
9
requiring consideration of certain factors; creating
9
certain presumption; allowing rebuttal of presumption
10
under certain circumstances; updating statutory
10
language; updating statutory references; and
11
providing an effective date.
11
12
12
13
BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
13
14
SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 22 O.S. 2021, Section 1105.2, is
14
15
amended to read as follows:
15
16
Section 1105.2. A. Following an arrest for a misdemeanor or
16
17
felony offense and before formal charges have been filed or an
17
18
indictment made, the arrested person may have bail set by the court
18
19
as provided in this act the Pretrial Release Act; provided there are
19
20
no provisions of law to the contrary.
20
21
B. When formal charges or an indictment has been filed, bail
21
22
shall be set according to law and the pretrial bond, if any, may be
22
23
reaffirmed unless additional security is required. Every judicial
23
24
district may, upon the order of the presiding judge for the
24
Req. No. 2895 Page 1

1
district, establish a pretrial bail schedule for felony or
1
2
misdemeanor offenses, except for traffic, wildlife, or water safety
2
3
offenses included in subsections B, C and D of Section 1115.3 of
3
4
Title 22 of the Oklahoma Statutes this title and those offenses
4
5
specifically excluded herein. The bail schedule established
5
6
pursuant to the authority of this act shall exclude any offense for
6
7
which bail is not allowed by law. The bail schedule authorized by
7
8
this act shall be set in accordance with guidelines relating to bail
8
9
and shall be published and reviewed by March 1 of each year by the
9
10
courts and district attorney of the judicial district.
10
11
C. Each judicial district shall utilize a validated pretrial
11
12
risk assessment tool to produce a risk rating to be presented to the
12
13
court that determines release conditions prior to the arrested
13
14
person’s initial appearance before a court. Results of the
14
15
assessment shall be provided to counsel for the defendant prior to
15
16
the initial appearance. The validated risk assessment tool shall
16
17
include:
17
18
1. Information related to the defendant’s:
18
19
a. criminal history,
19
20
b. ties to the community,
20
21
c. substance abuse history,
21
22
d. risk of flight, and
22
23
e. risk of danger to persons or the community; and
23
24
2. Consideration of the:
24
Req. No. 2895 Page 2

1
a. nature and circumstances of the offense,
1
2
b. seriousness of the offense, and
2
3
c. weight of the evidence against the defendant.
3
4
D. When determining bail or conditions of pretrial release, the
4
5
court shall presume the accuracy and validity of the pretrial risk
5
6
assessment administered pursuant to subsection C of this section and
6
7
shall set bail or conditions of release consistent with the risk
7
8
rating determined by the assessment. Such presumption may be
8
9
rebutted upon a showing by the state by clear and convincing
9
10
evidence that deviation from the recommendation of the pretrial risk
10
11
assessment is necessary to:
11
12
1. Secure the appearance of the defendant as required;
12
13
2. Protect the safety of any other person or the community; or
13
14
3. Comply with a specific statutory requirement governing the
14
15
charged offense.
15
16
E. If the court deviates from the recommendation of the
16
17
validated pretrial risk assessment, the court shall state on the
17
18
record or in a written order, the specific facts and evidence relied
18
19
upon to rebut the presumption and the reasons such evidence
19
20
demonstrates the necessity for deviation.
20
21
F. The pretrial bail shall be set in a numerical dollar amount.
21
22
If the person fails to appear in court as required the judge shall:
22
23
1. Rescind the bond and proceed to enter a judgment against the
23
24
defendant for the dollar amount of the pretrial bail if no private
24
Req. No. 2895 Page 3

1
bail was given at the time of release; provided, however, the court
1
2
clerk shall follow the procedures as set forth in Section 1301 et
2
3
seq. of Title 59 of the Oklahoma Statutes in collecting the
3
4
forfeiture amount against the person who fails to appear in court;
4
5
or
5
6
2. Rescind and forfeit the private bail if cash, property or
6
7
surety bail was furnished at the time of release as set forth in
7
8
Section 1301 et seq. of Title 59 of the Oklahoma Statutes.
8
9
D. G. When a pretrial program exists in the judicial district
9
10
where the person is being held, the judge court may utilize the
10
11
services of the pretrial release program when ordering pretrial
11
12
release, except when private bail has been furnished.
12
13
E. H. Upon an order for pretrial release or release on bond,
13
14
the person shall be released from custody without undue delay.
14
15
F. I. The court may require the person to be placed on an
15
16
electronic monitoring device as a condition of pretrial release.
16
17
G. J. In instances where an electronic monitoring device has
17
18
been ordered, the court may impose payment of a supervision fee.
18
19
Payment of the fee, in whole or according to a court-ordered
19
20
installment schedule, shall be a condition of pretrial release. The
20
21
court clerk shall collect the supervision fees.
21
22
SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
